{{Africa-myth-stub}}

The '''General Association of Buddhists''' was a Buddhist organisation formed in [[South Vietnam]] in 1951, regarded as the leading Buddhist organisation in the country. It was prominent during the 1963 [[Buddhist crisis]], a period of demonstrations and political instability which led to the [[1963 South Vietnamese coup|deposal]] of President [[Ngo Dinh Diem]]. After the [[fall of Saigon]], it effectively became outlawed under the communist government, who created their own Buddhist organisation under government control.

