This article lists '''[[Muslim scholars]] of the 1st century AH'''. During the 1st century AH (622 – 719 [[Common Era|CE]]), [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]] were the centers of knowledge. The [[Sahaba]] were the primary [[narrators of hadith]] during this period.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}
==List== {{columns-list|colwidth=30em| *[[Ubay ibn Ka'b]] (? &ndash; 22 AH) *[[Abd Allah ibn Mas'ud|Ibn Mas'ud]] (? &ndash; 32 AH) *[[Ka'ab al-Ahbar]] (? &ndash; 32 AH) *[[Wahb ibn Munabbih]] (? &ndash; 34 AH) *[[Ali]] (23 BH &ndash; 40 AH) *[[Abdullah ibn Sailam]] (? &ndash; 43 AH) *[[Ahmad ibn Tawoos]] (? &ndash; 53 AH?) *[[Abu Hurairah]] (? &ndash; 57 AH) *[[Masruq ibn al-Ajda']] (? &ndash; 62 AH?) *[[Alqama ibn Qays]] (? &ndash; 62 AH?) *[[`Abd Allah ibn `Abbas|Ibn Abbas]] (-3 AH &ndash; 68 AH) *[[Sulaym ibn Qays]] (? &ndash; 70 AH) *[[Abd-Allah ibn Umar|Ibn Umar]] (8 BH? &ndash; 74 AH) *[[Aswad ibn Yazid]] (? &ndash; 75 AH) *[[Ma'bad al-Juhani]] (? &ndash; 80 AH) *[[Sahl ibn Sa'd]] (? &ndash; 91 AH) *[[Urwah ibn Zubayr]] (? &ndash; 94 AH) *[[Said ibn Al-Musayyib]] (? &ndash; 94 AH) *[[Raja Ibn Haywah]] (? &ndash; ?) *[[Ali ibn Abu Talha]] (? &ndash; ?) *[[Uqbah ibn Amir]] (? &ndash; ?) }} ==References== <References/> {{clear}} ==See also== {{8A}}
[[Category:Muslim scholars of Islam| ]] [[Category:7th-century Islam]] [[Category:7th-century Islamic religious leaders]] [[Category:8th-century Islam]] [[Category:8th-century Islamic religious leaders]]

{{Shinto}} '''Myōjin''' (明神 'shining deity', 'illuminating deity', or 'apparent deity'<ref>Hori, Ichirō (1970). "[https://books.google.com/books?id=m6A3AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA114 Three Types of Redemption in Japanese Folk Religion.]" In R.J. Zwi Werblowsky and C. Jouco Bleeker (eds.), ''Studies in the History of Religions (supplements to Numen)'', vol. 18, ''Types of Redemption: Contributions to the Theme of the Study-Conference Held at Jerusalem 14th to 19th July 1968'' (p. 114). Leiden: Brill.</ref><ref>Okuyama, Michiaki. "[https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=NleE_GnZ_NgC&pg=PA101 Historicizing Modern Shinto: A New Tradition of Yasukuni Shrine,]" in S. Engler and G. P. Grieve, (eds.), ''Historicizing “Tradition” in the Study of Religion'' (p. 101). Walter de Gruyter.</ref>) or '''Daimyōjin''' (大明神 'great shining/apparent deity') was a title historically applied to Japanese ([[Shinto]]) [[Kami|deities]] (''kami'') and, by [[metonymy]], their [[Shinto shrine|shrines]].
The term is thought to have been derived from ''myōjin'' (名神 'notable deity'), a title once granted by the [[Imperial House of Japan|imperial court]] to ''kami'' deemed to have particularly impressive power and virtue and/or have eminent, well-established shrines and cults.<ref>Encyclopedia of Shinto, [http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=15 ''Myōjin'']</ref><ref>Encyclopedia of Shinto, [http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=260 ''Myōjin taisha'']</ref><ref>Encyclopedia of Shinto, [http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=17 ''Shingō'']</ref> This term is first attested in the ''[[Shoku Nihongi]]'', where offerings from the kingdom of Bohai ([[Balhae]]) are stated to have been offered to "the eminent shrines (名神社 ''myōjin-sha'') in each [[Provinces of Japan|province]]" in the year 730 ([[Tenpyō|Tenpyō 2]]).<ref>{{cite wikisource |title=續日本紀/卷第十 (Shoku Nihongi, vol. 10)|url=https://zh.wikisource.org/wiki/%E7%BA%8C%E6%97%A5%E6%9C%AC%E7%B4%80/%E5%8D%B7%E7%AC%AC%E5%8D%81}}</ref>{{efn|「庚戌。遣使奉渤海信物於諸國名神社。」}}
An epithet [[homophone|homophonous]] with this imperially bestowed title, "shining/apparent ''kami''" (written with different [[Chinese characters]]), was in popular usage from around the [[Heian period]] up until the end of the [[Edo period]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nakamura|first1=Issei|title=平安期における大明神号の成立とその意義 (The Formation and Significance of the Title Daimyoujin in the Heian Period)|journal=The Bukkyo University Graduate School review. Compiled by the Graduate School of Literature.|date=2009-03-01|issue=37|pages=83–89|url=http://archives.bukkyo-u.ac.jp/repository/baker/rid_DB003700003047}}</ref> coexisting with titles with more explicit Buddhist overtones such as ''[[gongen]]'' (権現 'incarnation')<ref name="Gongen">Encyclopedia of Shinto, [http://www2.kokugakuin.ac.jp/ijcc/wp/bts/bts_g.html#gongen ''Gongen'']</ref> or ''daibosatsu'' (大菩薩 'great [[bodhisattva]]').
[[File:Hatajirushi3.png|230px|thumb|left|A depiction of war banners used by the [[Taira clan]] (right) and Takeda Shingen (left). The leftmost banner (white with blue border and red lettering) carries the inscription ''[[Takeminakata|Suwa Hosshō Kamishimo Daimyōjin]]'' (諏訪法性上下大明神), while on the second banner from right (white with black lettering), flanking the legend ''[[Ise Shrine|Tenshō Kōtaijingū]]'' (天照皇大神宮) are inscribed ''Hachiman daibosatsu'' (八幡大菩薩) and ''[[Kasuga Shrine|Kasuga Daimyōjin]]'' (春日大明神).]]The earliest recorded usages of 'shining/apparent deity' are found in sources such as in the ''Sumiyoshi-taisha Jindaiki''<ref>{{cite web|title=住吉大明神大社神代記|url=http://kamnavi.jp/sumiyosi/}}</ref> (住吉大社神代記, "The [[Sumiyoshi taisha|Sumiyoshi Grand Shrine]]'s Records of the [[Age of the Gods]]", supposedly compiled in the year 731 but thought to actually be of a much later date), which refers to the [[Sumiyoshi sanjin|three Sumiyoshi deities]] as 'Sumiyoshi Daimyōjin' (住吉大明神),<ref name="Nakamura74">Nakamura (2009), p. 74.</ref> and the ''[[Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku]]''<ref>{{cite wikisource |title=日本三代實錄/卷第卌九 (Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku, vol. 49)|url=https://zh.wikisource.org/wiki/%E6%97%A5%E6%9C%AC%E4%B8%89%E4%BB%A3%E5%AF%A6%E9%8C%84/%E5%8D%B7%E7%AC%AC%E5%8D%8C%E4%B9%9D}}</ref> (completed in 901), which refers to '[[Matsunoo-taisha|Matsuo Daimyōjin]]' (松尾大明神).
While at first this title did not yet seem to have the Buddhist connotations that would later be associated with it, the connection between ''daimyōjin'' with the concept of ''[[honji suijaku]]'' (i.e. that the native ''kami'' are actually manifestations of Buddhist deities) was reinforced by an apocryphal utterance of [[Gautama Buddha|the Buddha]] often claimed to be derived from the ''Karuṇāpuṇḍarīka-sūtra'' (悲華經 "Compassionate Lotus [[Sutra]]"; Japanese: ''Hikekyō'')<ref>{{cite web|title=悲華經 (北涼 曇無讖譯)|url=http://tripitaka.cbeta.org/T03n0157|website=CBETA 漢文大藏經}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Compassionate Lotus Sutra (Taisho 0157)|url=http://www.ydsnrs.com/zjg/qita/world/0157.html}}</ref> quoted and alluded to in various medieval works, but which is not in the actual sutra's text: "After I have [[Parinirvana|passed into ''nirvana'']], during the [[Three Ages of Buddhism#Latter Day of the Law|Latter Day of the Law]], I shall appear as a great shining/apparent deity (大明神) and save all sentient beings."{{efn|「我滅度後、於末法中、現大明神、広度衆生。」}}<ref>Nakamura (2009), pp. 82-86.</ref>
Up until the early modern period, use of titles such as ''myōjin'' or ''gongen'' for many deities and their shrines were so widespread that these gods were rarely referred to by their proper names.<ref name="Nakamura74" /> For instance, both [[Takemikazuchi|the god]] of [[Kashima Shrine]] and the shrine itself were known as 'Kashima Daimyōjin' (鹿島大明神); [[Takeminakata|the deity]] enshrined in [[Suwa taisha|Suwa Grand Shrine]] was called 'Suwa Daimyōjin' (諏訪(大)明神), and so on. (cf. [[Hachiman|Hachiman-daibosatsu]] (八幡大菩薩) or [[Kumano shrine|Kumano Gongen]] (熊野権現)). After his death, [[Toyotomi Hideyoshi]] was deified under the name '[[Toyokuni Shrine (Kyoto)|Toyokuni Daimyōjin]]' (豊国大明神).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nomura|first1=Gen|title=豊国大明神号の創出過程に関する一考察 (On the deification of Toyotomi Hideyoshi as Toyokuni Daimyojin)|journal=Shigaku zasshi|date=2012-11-20|volume=121|issue=11|pages=1878-1900|url=http://ci.nii.ac.jp/naid/110009562128}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Lillehoj|first1=Elizabeth (ed.)|title=Art and Palace Politics in Early Modern Japan, 1580s-1680s|date=2011|publisher=Brill|isbn=978-9004206120|page=60|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-TMVF6kpoqkC&pg=PA60}}</ref>
Under [[Yoshida Shintō]], the conferral of ranks and titles like ''myōjin'' was institutionalized, with the sect issuing out authorization certificates to shrines for a fee.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Maeda|first1=Hiromi|title=Court Rank for Village Shrines. The Yoshida House’s Interactions with Local Shrines during the Mid-Tokugawa Period|journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies|date=2002|volume=29|issue=3/4|pages=325-358|url=https://nirc.nanzan-u.ac.jp/nfile/2785}}</ref><ref name>Encyclopedia of Shinto, [http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=372 ''Yoshida Shintō'']</ref> The sect considered the title to be higher than the overtly Buddhist ''gongen'' as part of the sect's [[Honji suijaku#Inversion|inversion of ''honji suijaku'']], an issue which became a point of contention with the Sannō Ichijitsu Shintō (山王一実神道) sect spearheaded by the [[Tendai]] monk [[Tenkai]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sugahara|first1=Shinkai|title=The Distinctive Features of Sannō Ichijitsu Shinto|journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies|date=1996|volume=23|issue=1/2|pages=61-84|url=https://nirc.nanzan-u.ac.jp/nfile/2587}}</ref><ref>Encyclopedia of Shinto, [http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=362 ''Sannō Shintō'']</ref>
When the Meiji government officially [[Shinbutsu bunri|separated Shinto from Buddhism]], official use of titles and terminology perceived as having Buddhist connotations such as ''(dai)myōjin'', ''(dai)gongen'' or ''daibosatsu'' by shrines were legally abolished and discouraged. However, a few deities/shrines are still often referred to as ''(dai)myōjin'' in popular usage even today. (E.g. [[Kanda Shrine|Kanda Myōjin]] in [[Chiyoda, Tokyo]], enshrining the deified [[Onryō|vengeful spirit]] of [[Taira no Masakado]]).
==See also== *''[[Shinbutsu-shūgō]]'', the syncretism of Buddhism and native ''kami'' worship *''[[Honji suijaku]]'' *''[[Shinbutsu bunri]]'', the official separation of Shinto from Buddhism during the Meiji period
