{{other uses}} {{use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}
'''Sāssān''' ([[Middle Iranian languages|Middle Iranian]] > [[Persian language|Persian]] ساسان, also known as Sasan), considered the eponymous ancestor of the [[House of Sasan|Sasanian (or Sassanid) Dynasty]] (ruled 224-651) in [[Persian Empire | Persia]], was "a great warrior and hunter" and a [[Zoroastrian]] high priest in [[Fars province|Pars]]. He lived some time near the fall of the [[Arsacid Empire|Arsacid (Parthian) Empire]] in the early 3rd century CE.
==Identity of Sasan== ===Medieval sources=== There are many slightly different stories concerning Sasan and his relation to [[Ardashir I]], the founder of the [[Sasanian Empire]]. The northern Iranian historian [[Muhammad ibn Jarir al-Tabari|Tabari]] mentions that Sasan married a princess of the [[Bazrangi|Bāzarangid]] family, the vassal dynasty of [[Fars province|Pārs]], and that Sasan was a grandfather of Ardashir I, while [[Papak]] is named as Ardashir I's father.{{sfn|Frye|1983|p=116-117}}
According to the [[Zoroastrian Middle Persian|Pahlavi]] book of [[Karnamak-i Artaxshir-i Papakan]], Sasan's wife was a daughter of a nobleman called Papak. The marriage was arranged by Papak after hearing that Sasan has "[[Achaemenid Empire|Achamenian (Achaemenid) blood in him]]". Their son was Ardashir I. Sasan vanishes shortly after Ardashir appears in the story and Papak is "considered the father of Ardashir".{{sfn|Frye|1983|p=116-117}}
These stories on different relations between Ardashir, Pāpak, and Sāsān have, according to Frye, a Zoroastrian explanation.{{sfn|Frye|1983|p=116-117}} Sasan was indeed the father of Ardashir and "disappears" from the story after the birth of Ardashir. Similar to the current Zoroastrian practices, Papak had then taken the responsibility of his daughter and her son Ardashir after Sasan "disappears" and is named afterwards as the father of Ardashir.{{sfn|Frye|1983|p=116-117}}
In the [[Ka'ba-ye Zartosht#Inscriptions|Kabe Zartosht inscription]] of Shapur I the Great, the four named persons "Sasan, Papak, Ardashir, Shapur" have different titles: Sasan is named as ''hwataw''{{sfn|Kohl et al|2008|p=114}} or ''xwadāy''{{sfn|Daryaee|2010|p=240}} ("the lord", usually given to sovereigns of small local principalities{{sfn|Kohl et al|2008|p=114}}), Papak as ''[[shah]]'', Ardashir as ''shāhanshāh'' ("King of Kings of the Sasanian Empire") and Shapur as "King of Kings of [[Iran]] and [[Aniran]]".{{sfn|Frye|1983|p=116-117}}
===Modern sources=== However, according to [[Touraj Daryaee]], Sasanian sources cannot be trusted because they were from the royal Sasanian archives, which were made by the court, in the words of Daryaee, "to fit the world-view of the late Sasanian world".{{sfn|Daryaee|2010}} Daryaee and several other scholars state that Sasan had his name from a deity who was known in many parts of [[Asia]] but not in Fars, the homeland of the Sasanians, which thus means that Sasan was an Iranian foreigner from the west or the east who had settled in Fars, whose inhabitants did not know about this deity he believed in.{{sfn|Daryaee|2010}} Sasan later managed to become the priest of the important Anahid temple in [[Estakhr]],{{sfn|Shahbazi|2005}} the capital of Fars. According to the [[Bundahishn]], which according to Daryaee was made independently and not by the Sasanian court, Sasan's daughter later married [[Papak]] and bore him Ardashir.{{sfn|Daryaee|2010}} Furthermore, the Bundahishn states that Sasan was the son of a certain Weh-afrid.{{sfn|Daryaee|2010}}
==Politics of the Sasanian family== The political ambition of Sasan was evoked by the troubles and weakness of the [[Parthian empire#Fall|last years of the Parthian empire]]. According to [[Tabari]], Papak managed to consolidate his power with the help of his own sons Shapur and [[Ardashir I|Ardashir]].{{sfn|Shahbazi|2005}} This is considered the beginning of [[Sasanian Empire#Origins and early history (205–310)|the Sasanian dynasty]].
Sasan's family became the rulers of the second Persian Empire and ruled over a great portion of western Asia (the first Persian Empire having been ruled by the dynasty of [[Cyrus the Great]]). The three founders of this new empire – that is, Papak and his two sons – are depicted and mentioned on the wall of the harem of Xerxes at [[Persepolis]], a remnant site of the [[Achaemenids]], a representation suggested to be the evidence of a claim to Achaemenid heritage likely later added.{{sfn|Shahbazi|2005}}<ref>{{Citation | title = Zur Genese altiranischer Motive IV | last = Calmeyer | first = Peter | journal = Archäologische Mitteilungen aus Iran | year = 1976 | pages = 65–67 | issn = 0066-6033 }}</ref>
Sasan is known for his efforts to try to bring Zoroastrianism back into the empire. He even encouraged Papak to take over the Parthian satrapy of Pars.<ref>{{Cite web | title = The Sassanian Dynasty (CE 224-641): The Zarathushti Renaissance | work = avesta.org | url = http://www.avesta.org/kerr/sas_part3.pdf }}</ref>
